Philippines Stocks: Ayala, Belle, Lepanto, Petron, SM Prime

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-07-13T04:53:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-13/philippines-stocks-ayala-land-lepanto-petron-sm-prime.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in Manila.  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 1.2 percent to
4,404, halting a two-day slide.  Builders:  Ayala Land Inc. (ALI)  , the nation’s biggest
developer, advanced 1.9 percent to 15.90 pesos, the first gain
in three days.  SM Prime Holdings Inc. (SMPH)  , the largest
mall developer, gained 1.6 percent to 11.68 pesos, its sharpest
advance this month.  Robinsons Land Corp. (RLC)  , the second-
largest mall operator, climbed 1.6 percent to 12.80 pesos.  The Philippine government has approved rules on taxation of
real estate investment trusts, paving the way for REIT trading,
said Hans Sicat, president of the nation’s stock exchange.  Consumer spending  was “stable” and “there are no
indications that it’s been weakened” by higher fuel costs, SM
Prime Chief Financial Officer Jeffrey Lim said. Real-estate
sales for the nation’s biggest developer “continue to be good”
even after the central bank’s monetary tightening, President
Antonino Aquino said separately.  Gold producers:  Lepanto Consolidated Mining (LC)  Co.’s Class A
shares (LC PM), which are reserved for Filipinos, jumped 11
percent to 1.12 pesos, the highest close based on prices going
back to January 1990, after gold jumped to an all-time high in
 Shanghai .  Philex Mining Corp. (PX)  , the nation’s biggest
metals producer, climbed 4.5 percent to 25.40 pesos, the highest
close based on prices going back to January 1990.  Spot gold jumped to a record 326 yuan a gram in Shanghai
today for bullion of 99.95 percent purity.  Belle Corp. (BEL)  , which is building a casino in Manila,
advanced 2.7 percent to 4.90 pesos, ending a two-day slump after
its directors approved a plan to raise 4.5 billion pesos ($104.5
million) in a rights offer to help fund the development.  Petron Corp. (PCOR)  , the largest of the nation’s two oil
refiners, fell 1.2 percent to 16.60 pesos, after BusinessWorld
reported the company’s second-quarter profit is likely to be
flat compared with its net income in the first quarter, citing
Chairman Ramon Ang. Ang hadn’t responded to  text messages  to his
mobile phone seeking comment.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
